The problem with your code is that you&#39;re first removing any _comma_, _\s_, or dot, from the string.

For example, _998,4_, becomes _9984_.  
Thus, the subsequent call to _replaceFirst_, finds nothing, so it replaces nothing.

I believe what you are intending to do is, first remove the group separators, and then replace the decimal separator.

```java
String cleanedInput = input.replaceAll(&quot;[. ]&quot;,&quot;&quot;);
cleanedInput = cleanedInput.replace(&quot;,&quot;,&quot;.&quot;);
```

Although this will not work for the last condition, where the group and decimal separator symbols are swapped.

```none
input:7,123.12   result:7.12312
```

You&#39;ll need to find their indices, to determine the number&#39;s format.

I created the following method, as an example.

```java
float parseFloat(String string) {
    string = string.replace(&quot; &quot;, &quot;&quot;);
    int comma = string.indexOf(&#39;,&#39;);
    int dot = string.indexOf(&#39;.&#39;);
    if (comma != -1 &amp;&amp; dot != -1) {
        if (comma &lt; dot) return Float.parseFloat(string.replace(&quot;,&quot;, &quot;&quot;));
        else {
            string = string.replace(&quot;.&quot;, &quot;&quot;);
            return Float.parseFloat(string.replace(&quot;,&quot;, &quot;.&quot;));
        }
    } else if (comma != -1) return Float.parseFloat(string.replace(&quot;,&quot;, &quot;.&quot;));
    else return Float.parseFloat(string.replace(&quot;.&quot;, &quot;&quot;));
}
```

